subsection.p:
For improper double integrals, the same symbols are used, but the meaning includes a
limit:
\boxed{\iint_R f\,dA=\lim_{A\to\infty}\iint_{R_A}f\,dA}
for an unbounded region, or
\boxed{\iint_R f\,dA=\lim_{\varepsilon\to0^+}\iint_{R_\varepsilon}f\,dA}
when a singular point has been removed and then allowed back in by a limit.

The region is a disk, and the density is radial, so use polar coordinates: 0\le r\le2,\qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi. The total water is
W \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^2 (10-r)r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 2\pi\int_0^2(10r-r^2)\,dr \amp= 2\pi\left[5r^2-\frac13r^3\right]_0^2 \amp= 2\pi\left(20-\frac83\right) \amp= \boxed{\frac{104\pi}{3}}.
The garden area is \pi(2)^2=4\pi. Therefore the average water density is \boxed{w_{\mathrm{avg}}=\frac{W}{4\pi}=\frac{26}{3}.}

subsubsection.p:
Use a midpoint sum: \iint_R r(x,y)\,dA\approx 4\sum r(x_i^*,y_j^*). For the data above,
\sum r(x_i^*,y_j^*) \amp= 3.2+4.1+4.6+3.8 \amp\qquad +2.4+3.5+5.0+4.2 \amp\qquad +1.1+2.0+3.1+2.7 \amp= 39.7.
So \boxed{\iint_R r(x,y)\,dA\approx 4(39.7)=158.8\text{ cm}\cdot\text{km}^2.}
